---------- Forwarded message ----------
From: Jamie Flournoy <jamie(-at-)white-mountain.org>

Jamie Flournoy wrote:

> I've seen the following pattern in a few messages lately...
>
> "I'm using the following products: [series of products, some of which
> are, shall we say, less than ideal]. They are configured as follows:
> [details, some of which are also less than ideal]. No workie. I know
> it's less than ideal but I can't start over, I have to make it work
> pretty much as is. Help!"
>
> Usually there is also a strange mantra uttered,
> "noootmaaaaaaaideseeeeeeshuuuun", which in context seems to be an
> incantation intended to defend against evil spirits which would cause
> others to lose respect for the utterer and potentially to lecture the
> utterer on how far from ideal their situation is, in case they are
> unaware.
>
> I think it would be simpler (and potentially far more humorous) if an
> abbreviated form of this mantra were to be used: NMD.
>
> Example:
>
> "I'm working with a client who has standardized on Windows for
> Workgroups [NMD]. Their current setup involves 4000 desktops in 88
> locations worldwide, all of which are bridged together [NMD!], and each
> of which is set up as a single ethernet segment using 10Base2 [NMD, NMD,
> NMD!!!].
>
> "LAN performance is less than ideal. The WAN links, which are OC-48
> connections [NMD], seem to have some capacity available, but the LAN is
> swamped from about 7am to 10pm (employees work long hours in order to
> get any work done, since the LAN is so slow). After hours it's a little
> better.
>
> "I tried changing one office to 10BaseT and installing a switch but that
> didn't help much. (Actually, the first switch I bought was defective; if
> I didn't know better I'd swear it was actually perspiring. I bought a
> slightly more expensive one and it seemed to be OK.) I think it has
> something to do with broadcast packets coming over the WAN connection,
> or maybe the LED's labeled 'COLL' on the front of the switch - I don't
> know what that means but it's on all the time so I'm wondering if that's
> related to the problem. BTW, I can't upgrade the OS on individual
> machines, but I can change LAN equipment including network cards, hubs,
> switches, etc. Any ideas?"
>
> :)

